    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1135614" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1135614" />
    <a title="erin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/56927-erin"><img alt="erin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1176361988p2/56927.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1135614?book_show_action=true">May 09, 2007</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="erin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="erin" href="/user/show/56927-erin">erin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">picky fantasy readers</span></div>

        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1135614" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4219534017493071756">&quot;Weak&quot; story??? &quot;Shallow world-building and characters&quot;????? What on earth?! I would say exactly the opposite. Compared to most of the shallow, sloppy fantasies that are being cranked out these days, this trilogy is absolutely singular in terms of story, world-building, and character development. This is one I come back to--it never disappoints. It was written in the 70s, and while McKillip admits being influenced by Tolkien, she succeeds in creating a unique, complex, and meticulously layered w</span>
  <span id="freeText4219534017493071756" style="display:none">"Weak" story??? "Shallow world-building and characters"????? What on earth?! I would say exactly the opposite. Compared to most of the shallow, sloppy fantasies that are being cranked out these days, this trilogy is absolutely singular in terms of story, world-building, and character development. This is one I come back to--it never disappoints. It was written in the 70s, and while McKillip admits being influenced by Tolkien, she succeeds in creating a unique, complex, and meticulously layered world that completely works on its own. Definitely in the high fantasy category. Unfortunately, her subsequent books haven't even come close (due to the complaints of the previous reviewer about this one).</span>
  <a data-text-id="4219534017493071756" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

