<div id="review_162159668" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/162159668" />
    <a title="Phoenix" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4905818-phoenix"><img alt="Phoenix" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1614359459p2/4905818.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/162159668?book_show_action=true">Aug 22, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Phoenix" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Phoenix" href="/user/show/4905818-phoenix">Phoenix</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4905818-phoenix?shelf=sex-and-gender">sex-and-gender</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4905818-phoenix?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4905818-phoenix?shelf=faerie-tales-and-folklore">faerie-tales-and-folklore</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4905818-phoenix?shelf=nature">nature</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4905818-phoenix?shelf=fantasy">fantasy</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer162159668&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer162159668" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3407325696412657951">3.5 stars. This was beautiful, albeit uneven. I guess early McKillip isn’t where it’s at for me.<br/><br/>This book is a lot like the world-building and folklore in Dark Souls games; much of the story is left up to the readers interpretation through vague mentions of past events and the settings. In fact, if you are a game narrative designer, I highly recommend you to read this trilogy especially for the latter chapters of Heir and Sea and Fire, second novel. There’s an awesome feminist revisiting of the </span>
  <span id="freeText3407325696412657951" style="display:none">3.5 stars. This was beautiful, albeit uneven. I guess early McKillip isn’t where it’s at for me.<br /><br />This book is a lot like the world-building and folklore in Dark Souls games; much of the story is left up to the readers interpretation through vague mentions of past events and the settings. In fact, if you are a game narrative designer, I highly recommend you to read this trilogy especially for the latter chapters of Heir and Sea and Fire, second novel. There’s an awesome feminist revisiting of the Fellowship of the Ring in the second novel as well. <br /><br />Morgon is the most reluctant hero in fantasy lit, hands down. Me and my reading buddy for this were constantly ribbing each other about how relatable he was every time he encountered another prophecy he was centred in and his response amounted to “—what part of I want to be a humble beer farmer do you NOT understand??” His love interest, Raederle, is also a wonderfully complex protagonist in her own right, and demonstrates how the struggle to come to terms with your inherent power can be harrowing. She is equal parts McKillip’s sorceress archetype and a vulnerable yet resourceful princess type. I would fight for her, and I can see why Morgon and many others do. You’ll be doing it alongside her though, because she does *not* wait around when there’s shit to do and her loved ones are in trouble. <br /><br />My biggest issues were to do with the vagueness of the riddles. Sometimes I felt like McKillip was in a conversation with herself about epic fantasy and old folklore, and I was an outsider wishing I had some key definitions or some other way to grasp what she meant by her many portents and myths. Perhaps I will take away more on rereading it, which I definitely will do in the future. <br /><br />I think this trilogy represents McKillip coming into her own and I love it for that. But I can also see how she was working out possible kinks in her style. I appreciate this trilogy for what it is, and for giving fantasy lit characters like Morgon, Raederle, Deth, Astrin, and Har. <br /><br /><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="3407325696412657951" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


